Message: Election Time! Please know the facts about Prop 15. It may sound good to jump on board....make large businesses pay more taxes.....but like always, it’s not them who will actually pay the tax. It will destroy the already struggling small businesses in California. There are few if any commercial properties in the Bay Area worth less than $3 million. Many small businesses are able to stay in business because they bought their building 20+ years ago. They cannot afford to pay this tax increase. Other small businesses rent and those leases would be largely triple net which means the property tax increase will be passed on to them immediately. For the few who have a gross lease the property owner would pass the tax when the lease renews. Businesses would then have to pass the tax increase to the consumers. Others would close or move out of state. Prop 15 will especially hurt minority owned businesses. Before we give the government anymore money, there needs to be accountability. Property tax revenues have been increasing for years, more funding for schools but yet it’s never enough. The problems we have are not a lack of revenue, it’s policies and management.

Okay, let's get the 2021 Washington Hikers and Climbers calendar contest started! Please read the rules below before submitting your one favorite photo from the year. CALENDAR CONTEST RULES: NOTE: Please add your photo to the album; do not post it in the comments. - Entries will be taken between November 8th and November 18th, and voting will occur simultaneously. - While photos may be submitted during the voting period, you will be at a disadvantage if you post late, as photos submitted earlier in the process will have more time to accumulate "likes," etc. - Photo must be your own. ONE ENTRY PER PERSON. Any additional entries will be removed. - Your photograph needs to be of Washington state, and accompanied by your full name and location of the photo. If you don't want to disclose the location of your photo, don't submit it. - Horizontal pictures work MUCH better for the calendar, and are strongly preferred, but we have used vertical pictures once or twice in the past. - While the photograph you enter may be watermarked, any photo actually chosen for the calendar will need to be sent to us "clean" (i.e., without watermark). For now, you can watermark. - You may vote for as many photos as you like (but if you vote for all of them, your vote will be meaningless :) ). - At midnight on November 18th, the photos with the most "likes" will be selected for the 2021 Washington Hikers and Climbers Calendar. - There may or may not be a second calendar comprised of photos selected by the Admins and Moderators of WHC (in the past, we have created an Administrators' Choice Calendar in addition to the one voted on by members). This year, due to the pandemic, we are outsourcing production and delivery of the calendar, so not all details regarding production and sale of the calendar have been determined. - Calendars should be available for purchase after the contest is over for a price yet to be determined, but no more than $25.00, which this year will not include the cost of shipping. Net profits will be donated to Search and Rescue groups around the state. - Members of the Administrative Team (admins and moderators) are not eligible for the contest.
Link Text: 2021 Washington Hikers and Climber calendar photo contest
Description:
Okay, let's get the 2021 Washington Hikers and Climbers calendar contest started!  Please read the rules below before submitting your one favorite photo from the year.

CALENDAR CONTEST RULES:

NOTE:  Please add your photo to the album; do not post it in the comments.

- Entries will be taken between November 8th and November 18th, and voting will occur simultaneously.  

- While photos may be submitted during the voting period, you will be at a disadvantage if you post late, as photos submitted earlier in the process will have more time to accumulate "likes," etc.

- Photo must be your own. ONE ENTRY PER PERSON. Any additional entries will be removed.

- Your photograph needs to be of Washington state, and accompanied by your full name and location of the photo. If you don't want to disclose the location of your photo, don't submit it. 

- Horizontal pictures work MUCH better for the calendar, and are strongly preferred, but we have used vertical pictures once or twice in the past.

- While the photograph you enter may be watermarked, any photo actually chosen for the calendar will need to be sent to us "clean" (i.e., without watermark).  For now, you can watermark.

- You may vote for as many photos as you like (but if you vote for all of them, your vote will be meaningless :) ).

- At midnight on November 18th, the photos with the most "likes" will be selected for the 2021 Washington Hikers and Climbers Calendar.

- There may or may not be a second calendar comprised of photos selected by the Admins and Moderators of WHC (in the past, we have created an Administrators' Choice Calendar in addition to the one voted on by members).  This year, due to the pandemic, we are outsourcing production and delivery of the calendar, so not all details regarding production and sale of the calendar have been determined.

- Calendars should be available for purchase after the contest is over for a price yet to be determined, but no more than $25.00, which this year will not include the cost of shipping. Net profits will be donated to Search and Rescue groups around the state.

- Members of the Administrative Team (admins and moderators) are not eligible for the contest.

Buy a house and get a 15 year fixed mortgage rather than a 30 year mortgage. Saves a lot of money in interest over the life of the loan. If you must get the 30 year mortgage, verify that there is no prepayment penalty. This gives you the flexibility of paying it off early if you are able. But it also gives you the option of making lower payments when times are tough... When you start your job, get an HSA account and not FSA and get the high deductible health insurance. It will lower your tax bracket and the money is yours to use. You also earn 40% in most cases after 10k!!! Never buy a car brand new! I’ve watched Escalades go from 100k (new) to 35k four years later. Get you an LLC (incorporate your name!!) and run it as an S Corp. Remember Jay-Z quote “I’m not a Businessman I’m a Business Maaaaaaaan....” Let that sink in. Build business credit! The loans are bigger and the interest rate is lower. Get a business bank account (in most cases this costs around $500 to start). Some people got two stimulus checks (one from Trump and one from the SBA). Also no fees. Go to Community College first and transfer into a four year college (unless you have scholarships to help mitigate the costs) as a Junior. School is a power move you must be able to secure the bag. Majors in STEM will always be needed, are in high demand and the skills can directly help the black community. Get with your peers from your graduating class and others together at homecoming on one day for two hours to plot and strategize how we can move our communities forward (commerce, politics, education, small businesses, real estate, etc...) If you want to support Black People, support Black Business and Black Institutions of Higher Education. Get life insurance for you (whole life) and your children (term) as soon as they are born (one thing is for sure is we will die..might as well leave your kids or family something extra). The sooner you get it, the cheaper it is. And you can borrow against it to fund certain projects. Also, the ones that pay out dividends are the best! They normally are associated with the market (money market accounts). IUL’s are great! Get the people in your immediate family to save collectively! If 10 people save $500/month, that’s 60k every year. You could buy 3 starter homes every year and in 4 years all ten of you are home owners. Buy on the same block or neighborhood if you can...this way you control the value of the homes (remember Monopoly!). We need to promote financial literacy. Building capital and creating equity to create generational wealth. Having financial freedom is everything! This is not being taught in the school curriculums or our education systems! We must do it ourselves! ***I need 10 people to copy and repost this on their pages and groups.*** copy from Vance Hendricks

End of A Season by David Harris Photo Credit 📷: Chris/@cdats Here we are at the end of a season, and as we depart today, we take away all the memories we have gathered during our stay. We reflect on friendships we have made, the ones we have lost and the ones we have. Our leaving today is mixed with happiness, sadness, and even a little regret for the things we should have done and did not get around to doing yet. The happiness is all the laughter we had while we were here, the sadness if for the departed friends whom we will never see again. Though we will never see them, their memories linger on. They will still be with us, even though they maybe gone. As we leave today we must remember the friends we have still, and the new ones we have made. As friends are so important within our daily lives. They share our happiness when our hearts are filled with joy. Their comforting arms are around us when times of sadness appear. We must always remember that we can never choose our family only our friends, so our friends we must always hold close to our heart.

Message: Hey all! We have two rooms available in our lovely 3 story row home. We're located at the intersection of three of the coolest neighborhoods in DC - Columbia Heights, Mt. Pleasant, and Adams Morgan. It's an easy walk to Meridian Hill Park, Safeway & Harris Teeter, and all the other stores & amenities in this busy neighborhood. The house is very spacious - the first floor is all common areas, including a living room, dining room, kitchen, and lovely back patio. Both available rooms are on the 2nd floor of the house, so will share a bathroom with 2 other people. Everything is fully furnished, except the available rooms, but even those have some leftover furniture in them. Our landlord is wonderful and super responsive to our needs as a house. Unfortunately, no pets allowed. Rent for the two available rooms is $800/month + utilities (electric, gas, water, WiFi) of about $50-100/month. The current housemates are three mid-20s, plant loving ladies who enjoy cooking and getting coffee together on the weekends. We like living in a clean and quiet home, with people who are respectful and COVID-conscious (and willing to buy more plants). It's important to us to find a housemate who we can all get along with and fits into our laid back vibe! If you're interested in living here, please send me an message and we will do a virtual tour of the house. Message me if interested!

Message: RIP Ronnys....I know some will probably say the food was cheap and bad....but let me tell you for me it was so much more than that. I remember when my father took me to the show in the late 60’s/early 70’s.....afterwards we went to Ronnys. Later on after my graveyard shift at O’hare waiting for Harris bank to open...we all went to Ronnys for $1.95 steak breakfast. At the Randolph location there was the AM/PM Disco where you could go dancing at damn near any time. At the Van Buren location there was a club downstairs. And finally years later after a play at the Schubert Theatre we went to Ronnys in the Thompson Center. Good luck and thanks for the memories

(Article via nypost) Puerto Rico’s governor endorsed President Trump’s re-election bid on Tuesday.

In an interview with Telemundo, Gov. Wanda Vázquez Garced announced her support for Trump and urged Puerto Ricans in the United States to vote for him on Nov. 3.

“I ask all Puerto Ricans who are listening to go vote,” Vázquez Garced said.

The Republican official was to participate in a campaign event with Trump in central Florida on Friday but it was canceled after the president tested positive for COVID-19, according to Miami Herald reporter Syra Ortiz-Blanes.

Vázquez Garced endorsed Trump despite his opposition to the island’s statehood, something she supports.

Puerto Rico is a US territory but people on the island are ineligible to vote in the presidential election.

In the Telemundo interview, Vázquez Garced was asked about Trump’s infamous visit to the island where he tossed paper towels to Puerto Ricans devastated by Hurricane Maria in 2017.

Message: City of Chicago wants to receive $1 instead of $300,000 for the old Firehouse in Jefferson Park. The property will not be Tax Exempt. Please Join our Cause! Dear Friend of Copernicus, As you might know, the Copernicus Foundation is trying to buy the abandoned firehouse at 4841 N. Lipps from the City of Chicago in a negotiated sale. The Foundation would renovate the property keeping its historic façade and having it be part of our campus. The Copernicus Foundation is willing to pay $300,000 for the property which the city appraised at $208,000. Sadly, the city appears to be accepting an offer from an outside developer, Ambrosia Homes, who will only be paying $1 for the property. There are a number of steps that have to be taken before that sale is final, so we are asking for your support in trying to stop the sale. Please visit our website at www.FightForTheFirehouse.com to express your support of the Copernicus Foundation by signing our petition. The site will also allow you to send an e-mail directly to your Alderman asking him not to vote for the negotiated sale of the firehouse to Ambrosia Homes. Please pass this information along to any of your friends and colleagues and also SHARE IT ON YOUR SOCIAL MEDIA so we will be able to show Mayor Lightfoot and the Aldermen that the community supports the Copernicus Foundation in its endeavor to develop this property in the best interests of our community.
